37","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1137":"1137","ABT 1165":"omkring 1165","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1212":"1212","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","about 1167":"omkring 1167","environ 1138":"omkring 1138","Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgien","Grimbergen, Brabant Flamand, Belgique":"Grimbergen, Vlaams-Brabant, Belgien","Ninove, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgien"},"nl":{"1137–1190":"1137–1190","1149–1188":"1149–1188","1136–1200":"1136–1200","1165–1200":"1165–1200","1167–1212":"1167–1212","1105–1167":"1105–1167","1110–1168":"1110–1168","1190":"1190","before 1167":"vóór 1167","1110":"1110","1165":"1165","abt 1137":"circa 1137","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1137":"1137","ABT 1165":"circa 1165","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1212":"1212","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","about 1167":"circa 1167","environ 1138":"circa 1138","Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, België","Grimbergen, Brabant Flamand, Belgique":"Grimbergen, Vlaams-Brabant, België","Ninove, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, België"},"en":{"1137–1190":"1137–1190","1149–1188":"1149–1188","1136–1200":"1136–1200","1165–1200":"1165–1200","1167–1212":"1167–1212","1105–1167":"1105–1167","1110–1168":"1110–1168","1190":"1190","before 1167":"before 1167","1110":"1110","1165":"1165","abt 1137":"about 1137","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1137":"1137","ABT 1165":"about 1165","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1212":"1212","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","about 1167":"about 1167","environ 1138":"about 1138","Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium":"Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium","Grimbergen, Brabant Flamand, Belgique":"Grimbergen, Flemish Brabant, Belgium","Ninove, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde van Ninove was born in 1137, in Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium, her father, Gerard II van Ninove, was 33 and her mother, Gisela VAN PETEGHEM, was 27. She had at least 2 sons with Gerard II Van Berthout Heer van Grimbergen. She died in 1190, in her hometown, at the age of 53, and was buried in Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium."},"et":{"1137–1190":"1137–1190","1149–1188":"1149–1188","1136–1200":"1136–1200","1165–1200":"1165–1200","1167–1212":"1167–1212","1105–1167":"1105–1167","1110–1168":"1110–1168","1190":"1190","before 1167":"enne 1167","1110":"1110","1165":"1165","abt 1137":"umbes 1137","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1137":"1137","ABT 1165":"umbes 1165","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1212":"1212","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","about 1167":"umbes 1167","environ 1138":"umbes 1138","Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Grimbergen, Brabant Flamand, Belgique":"Grimbergen, Vlaams-Brabant, Belgia","Ninove, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fi":{"1137–1190":"1137–1190","1149–1188":"1149–1188","1136–1200":"1136–1200","1165–1200":"1165–1200","1167–1212":"1167–1212","1105–1167":"1105–1167","1110–1168":"1110–1168","1190":"1190","before 1167":"ennen vuotta 1167","1110":"1110","1165":"1165","abt 1137":"noin 1137","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1137":"1137","ABT 1165":"noin 1165","1136":"1136","1168":"1168","1212":"1212","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1188":"1188","about 1167":"noin 1167","environ 1138":"noin 1138","Ninove, East Flanders, Belgium":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Grimbergen, Brabant Flamand, Belgique":"Grimbergen, Vlaams-Brabant, Belgia","Ninove, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Ninove, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fr":{"1137–119